window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>1>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : UTILITY SCHOOL OF THOUGHT","question":"The table below represents a traveller's consumption or bottles of Coca-Cola. Study the table carefully and answer the questions that follow.     No. of bottles Total Utility Marginal Utility 1 15 152 29 F 3 42 134 D 12 5 65 G 6 75 H 7 E O     (a) Complete the missing figure D, E, F G and H","images":[],"marking_scheme":"D = TU4 = TU3 + MU4  D = 42 + 12= 54    E = TU7 =  TU6 + MU7 = 75 + 0 = 75    F=MU2=TU2 - TU12 - 1  F=29 - 151 = 14  OR   F = MU2 = TU2 - TU1 = 29 - 15= 14    G=MU5=TU5-TU45-4  =65 - 541 =  11    H=MU6=TU6 - TU56 - 5  =75 - 656 - 5 = 10","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>1>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Draw the demand curve for the traveller's consumption of Coca-Cola. (The use of a graph sheet is essential)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"To draw the demand curve, there must be information on both quantities and prices. In equilibrium, MU = P, therefore the marginal utility column represents prices.","marks":"10","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>1>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : DIMINISHING MARGINAL UTILITY AND LAW OF DEMAND","question":"Explain the law of diminishing marginal utility as the basic for the slope of the traveller's demand curve","images":[],"marking_scheme":"According to the law, marginal utility falls when quantity consumed increases.   In equilibrium MU = P. Therefore, for MU to fall, price must fall to encourage the consumer to consume more. In other words, it is as price falls that quantity demanded increases as shown in the demand curve.","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>2>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : CONCEPT","question":"The table below represents the cost function of a poultry farm. The price of a crate of egg is $21. Use the information contained in the table to answer the questions that follow.    Quantity of Egg (In crates) Total Cost (In $)Marginal Cost $0 50501 5552 6273 75134 96215 125 296 162 377 20341 8 24845    (a) What is the fixed cost of the farm?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Quantity of Egg (In crates) Total Cost (In $)Marginal Cost $0 50501 5552 6273 75134 96215 125 296 162 377 20341 8 24845   $50 (When output is zero, total cost is $50. This implies that fixed cost is $50).","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>2>b>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : EXPLICIT AND IMPLICIT COSTS","question":"The table below represents the cost function of a poultry farm. The price of a crate of egg is $21. Use the information contained in the table to answer the questions that follow.    Quantity of Egg (In crates) Total Cost (In $)Marginal Cost $0 50501 5552 6273 75134 96215 125 296 162 377 20341 8 24845  Calculate the marginal cost at each level of output","images":[],"marking_scheme":"MCo = 50    MC1=55-501-0=51=5  OR   MC1 = 55 - 50 = 5    MC2=62-552-1=71=7    MC3=75-623-2=131=13    MC4=96-754-3=211=21    MC5=125-965-4=291=29    MC6=162-1256-5=371=37    MC7=203-1627-6=411=41    MC8=248-2038-7=451=45","marks":"9","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>2>b>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : PROFIT MAXIMIZATION","question":"The table below represents the cost function of a poultry farm. The price of a crate of egg is $21. Use the information contained in the table to answer the questions that follow.    Quantity of Egg (In crates) Total Cost (In $)Marginal Cost $0 50501 5552 6273 75134 96215 125 296 162 377 20341 8 24845  What is the profit maximizing output of the farm?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The profit maximizing output is 4 crates of eggs.  This is when MC = P","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>2>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Draw the demand curve for the farm","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"D = AR  (AR = $21)","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>3>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : APPLICATION OF ELASTICITY ON REVENUE","question":"With an appropriate illustration, explain the circumstance in which an increase in output of a producer would    Decrease his sales revenue","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"An increase in output would decrease the sales revenue of a producer where demand is price inelastic. The explanation is as follows  - An increase in output, given demand, will reduce the price and increase the quantity demanded  - If demand is price inelastic, the increase in the quantity demanded will be proportionately smaller than the reduction in the price.  - therefore sales revenue will decrease.     Illustration   A 405 fall in price is matched by a 105 increase in quantity demanded - i.e demand is price inelastic.  PeriodPriceQuantity DemandedSales revenue$$110050050,00026055033,000  or","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>3>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : APPLICATION OF ELASTICITY ON REVENUE","question":"With an appropriate illustration, explain the circumstance in which an increase in output of a producer would   Increase his sales revenue","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"An increase in output would increase the sales revenue of a producer where the demand for the product is price elastic. The explanation is as follows:  - An increase in output given demand, will reduce the price and increase the quantity demanded  - If demand is price elastic, the increase in the quantity demanded will be proportionately greater than the reduction in price.  - Therefore, sales revenue will increase.     Illustration   A 10% fall in price is matched by a 40% increase in quantity demanded i.e demand is price elastic.  PeriodPriceQuantity DemandedSales Revenue$$110050050,00029070063,000  or","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>4>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Define increase in supply","images":[],"marking_scheme":"An increase in supply refers to a situation where producers are willing and able to sell more of a good or service at every price level than before. This shift is represented by a rightward shift of the supply curve on a graph.    An increase in supply can occur due to various factors, such as advancements in technology, a decrease in production costs, an increase in the number of suppliers, or favorable government policies. As a result, more of the good or service is available in the market, potentially leading to lower prices if demand remains constant.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>4>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION : EFFECT OF CHANGE IN SUPPLY & DEMAND ON EQUILIBRIUM PRICE & QUANTITY","question":"With the aid of diagrams, explain the effect of an increase in the supply of fish on the price of beef.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"- An increase in the supply of fish, other things being equal, will reduce the price of fish  - Fish will become relatively cheaper than beef  - As a result, the demand for beef will decrease.  - Given the supply of beef, the price of beef will fall  - The extent to which the price of beef will fall depends on the price elasticities of supply and demand.    Diagrams.  Increase in supply of Fish     &nbsp &nbsp&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Effect on the price of Beef","marks":"16","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>5>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : CONSUMER EQUILIBRIUM","question":"What is the equilibrium of a consumer?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The equilibrium of a consumer is a situation in which his satisfaction or utility from spending his income on various goods and services is maximized.","marks":"5","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>5>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : CONSUMER EQUILIBRIUM","question":"Explain how a consumer attains equilibrium in spending his income","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Alternative 1   In this approach, it is assumed that utility or satisfaction is measured in terms of money. In this case, the consumer buys as much of a commodity as would make its price exactly equal to his estimate of the money value of the marginal utility of the commodity. In symbols, MUx = Px. This is the equilibrium condition  or    Alternative 2   In this approach, it is assumed that utility is measured in units of utility called utils. In this case, the consumer arranges his consumption in such a way that the marginal utilities of the commodities are proportional to their prices.   MUxMUy=PxPyThisistheequilibriumcondition     Alternative 3   In this approach also it is assumed that utility is measured in utils.  In this case, the consumer arranges his purchases in such a way that the marginal utility per unit of money spend on a commodity is the same for all commodities purchased. In symbols,   MUxPx=MUyPyThisistheequilibriumcondition     Alternative 4   Again, utility is measured in utils  In this approach a consumer arranges his purchases in such a way that for each commodity the arginal utility equals the utility of the price.  In symbols, MUx = \u2227Px  In addition, whatever approach is used, candidates must go on to show:  - What happens when the equilibrium condition is no longer satisfied because price rises or falls.  - How equilibrium can be attained finally.    For example, in alternative 1, if the price of x, Px falls, the equilibrium condition would no longer be satisfied. Marginal utility of x, MUx, would be greater than the Px i.e MUx > Px    To establish an equilibrium, MUx must fall to the same level as Px. This happens when the consumer buys more of X.  On the other hand, if the Px rises, again the equilibrium condition would not be satisfied. MUx x. To attain an equilibrium, the consumer would buy less of x to raise the MUx to the same level as Px.","marks":"15","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>6>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION (1) : INTRODUCTION","question":"Explain with examples the following types of production:  (i) Primary (ii) Secondary (iii) Tertiary","images":[],"marking_scheme":"i. Primary production; This involves the extraction of raw materials in their natural form from land, sea and air e.g products from agriculture, mining, quarrying, fishing.  ii. Secondary production: This entails the conversion of basic raw materials or semi-finished commodities to their final forms that are acceptable to the consumers i.e the raw materials extracted from soil and sea are processed and transformed into garri, clothes , houses, motor cars etc.  iii. Tertiary production: This type of production includes commercial and professional services. All those who provide commercial services such as wholesalers, retailers and transporters are involved in the tertiary production. It also includes persons who perform direct or professional services such as doctors, lawyers and barbers.","marks":"12","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>6>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION (1) : INTRODUCTION","question":"Give two reasons why primary production predominates in developing countries.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"i. inadequate capital  ii. low technology  iii. shortage of relevant skills  iv. inadequate infrastructure  v. inadequate entrepreneurial capacity  vi. small market size  vii. lack of research support to push the secondary and tertiary sectors.","marks":"8","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>7>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BUSINESS ORGANISATION : PARTNERSHIP","question":"What is partnership?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A partnership is a form of business organization in which between two and twenty individuals enter into an agreement, to run a business.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>7>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BUSINESS ORGANISATION : PARTNERSHIP","question":"State any two advantages and any two disadvantages of a partnership","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Advantages of a partnership are   - Individuals pooling resources together can generate more capital  - It is easier to specialize, since each of the partners may bring different skills and expertise into the business  - Two heads are better than one and so decisions could be more rational  - Where there are many partners, the death of one of the partners may not mean the end of the business  - Privacy in conducting business    Disadvantages are:  - Capital is still relatively limited as it cannot float shares  Capital depends mainly on the resources of the partners  - Decision making is difficult as the partners sometimes disagree  - Depending on the number of partners, the death of one partner may result in the collapse of the business  - When there is a debt the partners may lose not only the capital they have invested in the business but other properties as well. Liability is unlimited.  - It is not a legal entity  - The activities of one partner may ruin the organization","marks":"16","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>8>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"INDUSTRY & INDUSTRIALISATION : COMMERCIALISATION & PRIVATISATION","question":"What is privatization?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Privatization is the transfer to private ownership and control assets or enterprises which were previously under public ownership.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>8>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : INTRODUCTION","question":"Give four reasons for government participation in economic activities in your country.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Necessity: Sometimes private investors are unwilling to undertake businesses with low profit.  - Inadequate domestic capital: At times, domestic private capital is not available or is inadequate for large and risky projects. Hence, the government comes in.  - Ideology: some governments establish or take over certain enterprises on ideological /political grounds e.g a government wishing to change from capitalist to socialist system would place most industries in the public sector.  - For national self preservation: Projects in this category are usually for defence or strategic needs rather than economic, such as production of ammunition, petroleum, electricity, etc.  - Protection from private monopolies: Private monopolies tend to create artificial scarcity so as to raise prices and so the government comes in   - To avoid waste through unnecessary competition: leaving certain enterprise in private hands may result in too much duplication, with too many firms each producing under capacity.  - Where it is felt that government control is necessary for carrying out government policy e.g the Central Bank  - To avoid subsidizing a private enterprise for too long. Some industries are unable to support themselves and have to be subsidized by Government for long periods. As such, it is better for the Government to take over.  - To provide employment  - To provide basic amenities  - To create wealth for the common good  - To bring about even development.","marks":"16","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>9>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"INDUSTRY & INDUSTRIALISATION : INTRODUCTION","question":"Distinguish between Location of industries and localization of industries","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Location industries refers to the choice of a site for a firm in an industry. The factors taken into consideration in choosing a site may be economic or political.  On the other hand, localization of industries refers to the concentration of firms of an industry in a particular area.","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>9>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"INDUSTRY & INDUSTRIALISATION : INTRODUCTION","question":"Describe any three advantages and any two disadvantages of locating industries in rural areas.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Advantages of locating industries in the rural areas are:  - It checks the dirt of young people from the rural areas to the towns and cities  - Labour is cheaper in the rural areas  - Transportation and accommodation problems of staff are likely to be less  - The industrial atmosphere would be more peaceful, free from traffic congestion.  - A market would be provided for local raw materials and skills.  - Land is likely to be more easily available in the rural areas  - It will be easier for the firm to get raw materials in the rural areas  - It would bring about development and improvement in the standard of living in the area.    Disadvantages of locating industries in the rural areas are  - Basic infrastructure may not be available. The industry may have to provide such infrastructure at its own expense, thus rasing the unit cost of production.  - Skilled workers from the urban areas may be unwilling to work in the rural areas, unless they are given substantial incentives.  - There may not be suitable accommodation that could be rented for use as factories and offices. The business may have to build its own houses at great expense.  - It is more difficult for workers to find alternative employment if they lose their jobs for one reason or the other.  - Damages and losses may be suffered when moving the goods to the markets in urban areas  - The market for finished goods may be small or non-existent in the rural areas.","marks":"15","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>10>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"MONEY : FUNCTIONS OF MONEY","question":"Explain the function of money as a   (i) Measure of value (ii) Store of value","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Money as a measure of value means that money serves as a common denominator for measuring the relative values of goods and services. In other words, money is used to express the value of one commodity in terms of other commodities. As the values of commodities are stated in terms of money, their relative values are automatically established. For example, if a cutlass sells for $4 and a table is priced at $40, it means one table is worth 10 cutlasses.     - Money as a store of value means that money makes it possible for a person to save part of his current income or produce for later use. Whatever is produced can be sold and kept in the form of money for future use. This is because goods may be perishable. Services are also intangible. It will be difficult for a teacher or a doctor to save part of his output in the absence of money.","marks":"10","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>10>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"INFLATION & DEFLATION : EFFECT","question":"Show how inflation affects these two functions of money","images":[],"marking_scheme":"How inflation affects money as a measure of value   Since inflation reduces the value of money, its function as a measure of value is affected. If the inflation is general, prices may rise to the same extent so that relative values of commodities would remain unchanged. On the other hand, if the inflation affects some commodities more than others then the relative values between commodities would change.     How inflation affects money as a store of value   When there is inflation money loses value. More money is exchanged for a particular commodity. In other words, a given unit of money exchanges for less goods. In such circumstances, people hesitate to store their wealth in terms of money. The money saved would lose part of its value. It would exchange for less output in future than now. In such circumstances, people prefer to save in terms of assets which are likely to appreciate in value like land and buildings.","marks":"10","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>11>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : COMMERCIAL BANKS","question":"What is a commercial bank?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A commercial bank is a financial institution, usually established as a joint stock company with the aim of making profit. It usually grants short-term and medium-term loans.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>11>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK","question":"Describe any four ways by which the Central bank controls the amount of credit given by the commercial banks","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The various ways by which the central bank controls the amount of credit given by the commercial banks are:  - through the manipulation of the Bank Rate: if the central bank wants to encourage the commercial banks to lend more it would reduce the Bank Rate. If it wants to discourage the commercial banks from lending, it would raise the Bank Rate.    - Open Market Operations: The central bank sells securities on the open market to reduce the reserves of the commercial banks and so limit their ability to lend. On the other hand, if it wants to encourage the commercial banks to lend, it buys securities on the open market to increase the cash reserves of the commercial banks.    - Special deposits: By calling on the commercial banks to make special deposits with it, the central bank reduces the reserves the commercial banks are free to use to give credit.    - Through the manipulation of the cash minimum reserve ratio/liquidity ratio. The cash ratio is raised when it is desired to discourage lending by the commercial banks on the other hand, it is reduced when it is desired to encourage them to lend.    - Directives/Selective credit control: The central bank has authority to give direct instructions to the commercial banks as to whether or not they should increase their lending. Sometimes it gives directives as to sectors of the economy that should be favoured in granting loans.    - Moral suasion: Sometimes by merely announcing to the commercial banks its policy on lending, the central bank succeeds in getting the commercial banks to behave as expected.    - Funding: The central bank can convert short-term securities into long-term securities and so prevent an increase in the reserves of the commercial banks.","marks":"16","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>12>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : PRINCIPLE OF TAXATION","question":"What is incidence of taxes","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The incidence of taxes refers to where the burden of a tax finally rests.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2010>12>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2010","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : PRINCIPLE OF TAXATION","question":"Explain four principles of taxation","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Equity: Tax should be based on a person's ability to pay and there should be equality of sacrifice i.e the burden of tax should be according to one's ability.  - Certainty: Tax payers should know the amount they are expected to pay, when and how to pay it  - Convenience: The method and time of tax collection should be convenient to the tax payers.  - Economy: The amount spent in the course of collecting the tax should be smaller than the amount of tax revenue collected  - Flexibility: The tax system should not be rigid  - Neutrality: The tax should not unduly affect people's willingness to work, save and invest.  - Simplicity: The tax laws should be easy to understand.","marks":"16","difficulty":"2"}];